  "17-18": (
    caption: [The (cid:4) oxidation of a branched-chain fatty acid (phy- tanic acid) in peroxisomes. Phytanic acid has a methyl-substituted (cid:2) carbon and therefore cannot undergo (cid:2) oxidation. The combined action of the enzymes shown here removes the carboxyl carbon of phytanic acid to produce pristanic acid, in which the (cid:2) carbon is unsubstituted, allowing (cid:2) oxidation. Notice that (cid:2) oxidation of pristanic acid releases propionyl-CoA, not acetyl-CoA. This is further catabo- lized as in Figure 17–12. (The details of the reaction that produces pris- tanal remain controversial.) c17FattyAcidCatabolism.indd Page 686 20/09/12 11:03 AM user-F408 c17FattyAcidCatabolism.indd Page 686 20/09/12 11:03 AM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop 686],
