  "17-19": (
    caption: [Formation of ketone bodies from acetyl-CoA. Healthy, well-nourished individuals produce ketone bodies at a relatively low rate. When acetyl-CoA accumulates (as in starvation or untreated diabetes, for example), thiolase catalyzes the condensation of two acetyl-CoA molecules to acetoacetyl-CoA, the parent compound of the three ketone bodies. The reactions of ketone body formation occur in the matrix of liver mitochondria. The six-carbon compound (cid:2)-hydroxy-(cid:2)-methylglutaryl- CoA (HMG-CoA) is also an intermediate of sterol biosynthesis, but the enzyme that forms HMG-CoA in that pathway is cytosolic. HMG-CoA lyase is present only in the mitochondrial matrix.],
